article.headline: Wolf Pack has Snyder reply: 23 points
article.linkText: Nevada beats Hawaii, still in WAC title hunt
article.story: RENO, Nev. (AP) -- Kirk Snyder scored 23 points to lead Nevada to its 14th straight home win and keep the Wolf Pack in the hunt for a share of the Western Athletic Conference title with a 77-64 win Thursday night over Hawaii. Todd Okeson added 18 points for Nevada (19-8, 12-5), which has won 10 of its last 12 games and is now in second place, one game behind UTEP with one regular season game remaining. Michael Kuebler scored a team-high 17 points on 5-of-7 shooting from 3-point range for Hawaii (19-9, 11-6 WAC), which trailed 31-16 at the half on 22 percent shooting from the field. Nick Fazekas had 11 points and Kevinn Pinkney added nine points and a game-high eight rebounds for Nevada, which outscored Hawaii 17-4 the last 11 minutes of the first half capped by Snyder's 19-foot jumper just before the buzzer. Hawaii scored the first six points of the second half and cut Nevada's lead to 36-29 after Phil Martin scored eight points in a row and Kuebler hit a 3-pointer with 15:40 remaining. Okeson answered with a 3-pointer to start a 15-5 run that included consecutive slam dunks by Snyder and another Okeson 3-point goal for a 51-34 lead at 10:22. Trailing 59-47, Hawaii made one last run when Kuebler hit consecutive 3-pointers and Jason Carter added another to slice Nevada's lead to 63-56 with 5:20 remaining. But the Rainbow Warriors could pull no closer as Okeson, Fazekas and Snyder combined for 6-of-6 free-throw shooting down the stretch. Haim Shimonovich scored 11 points and grabbed seven rebounds and Martin and Jeff Blackett each finished with 10 points for Hawaii. Nevada is now 14-0 at home this season, it's best record at home since the school moved up to Division I before the 1969-70 season. The Wolf Pack are 19-0 when leading at the half this season, 0-9 when trailing at halftime. UTEP closes the season Saturday at Boise State while Nevada hosts San Jose State.
